      "role": "user",
      "content": "that seems okay, but i think it might crash if the function returns something other than a simple boolean or if it raises an error occasionally. some of our tests throw exceptions sometimes due to network timeouts, and we want to count that as a form of flakiness too.\n\ncan u update it? also, i want to make sure it's robust. try running it against this:\n\n```python\ndef test_exception_flaky():\n    # sometimes works, sometimes crashes\n    if random.random() < 0.5:\n        return True\n    else:\n        raise ValueError(\"connection error\")\n\ndef test_always_error():\n    # always crashes\n    raise ValueError(\"always fails\")\n\n# If it's flaky (even due to errors), it should return True\n# If it's consistently erroring, it's \"stable\" (not flaky)\nassert detect_flakiness(test_exception_flaky) == True\nassert detect_flakiness(test_always_error) == False\n```",
      "source": "evaluator"
